The paper discusses the use of technology and social science to understand mathematical practice, specifically through crowdsourcing and social machines. This suggests a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), cybernetics (cs.CY), deep learning (cs.DL), and social and information networks (cs.SI).
